        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1881-11-23T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1881-11-23T00:00:00-05:00" n="267" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d267">
                <head>No. 263.<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Morton</persName>
                            to Mr. <persName type="to">Blaine</persName>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1881-11-23">
                            <hi rend="italic">November</hi> 23,
                            1881</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Have seen Mr. Gambetta and urged the abrogation of the pork decree. He says
                        there exists serious public apprehension of danger from consumption American
                        pork, which he personally does not share, but finds necessity of some reason
                        for abrogation of decree which would satisfy public, and wished to know if
                        our government could not inaugurate public inspection of <hi rend="italic">meats</hi> for export; this would greatly facilitate satisfactory
                        settlement. He understood other governments had made similar suggestion. He
                        expressed himself as convinced of exaggerated character of supposed danger
                        and as personally favorable to friendly action, but also as obliged to
                        confront prejudice which could not be overlooked.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>MORTON.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
